{
  "executive_summary": "Architecture for a real-time ML delivery time estimation service with a clean separation between the serving path (optimized for sub-100ms P99 latency at checkout) and the training path (weekly batch retraining pipeline). The design uses a model registry as the central coordination point between training and serving, enabling safe rollbacks and blue-green model deployments. Kept deliberately simple for a 4-person team — no Kubernetes, no feature store, no microservice sprawl.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Prediction API",
        "responsibility": "Serves real-time delivery time predictions. Stateless HTTP service that loads the active model into memory on startup and serves inference requests. Handles feature encoding/normalization inline. Returns predicted minutes + confidence interval.",
        "boundaries": "Owns only inference-time logic. No training code, no data pipeline code. Reads model artifacts from Model Registry. Receives pre-validated input from the checkout service."
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Registry",
        "responsibility": "Versioned storage of trained model artifacts, metadata (metrics, training date, dataset hash, feature schema), and the pointer to the currently active model version. Single source of truth for which model is live.",
        "boundaries": "Stores artifacts and metadata only. Does not execute training or inference. Implemented as an S3 bucket with a metadata table (DynamoDB or Postgres) — not a heavyweight MLflow deployment."
      },
      {
        "name": "Training Pipeline",
        "responsibility": "Weekly batch job that pulls recent delivery data, engineers features, trains the model, evaluates it against holdout set and the current production model, and publishes the candidate model to the Model Registry. Includes automated quality gates.",
        "boundaries": "Runs offline only. Never touches the serving path directly. Writes to Model Registry. Reads from the Delivery Data Store. Orchestrated by a simple scheduler (cron or Airflow single-DAG)."
      },
      {
        "name": "Delivery Data Store",
        "responsibility": "Stores historical delivery records including actual delivery times (labels), order features, and contextual data (weather, courier load at time of order). Append-only.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the canonical delivery dataset. Ingests from the logistics platform's operational database via a nightly ETL or CDC stream. Training Pipeline reads from here; Prediction API does NOT."
      },
      {
        "name": "Shadow Evaluation Service",
        "responsibility": "Runs the candidate model in shadow mode against live traffic for a configurable window (e.g., 24 hours) before promotion. Compares candidate predictions against the active model and logs divergence metrics. Provides the go/no-go signal for promotion.",
        "boundaries": "Read-only on live traffic. Adds no latency to the checkout path (async). Writes evaluation results to the Model Registry metadata."
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Deployment Controller",
        "responsibility": "Handles model promotion and rollback. On promotion: updates the active model pointer in the Registry, triggers a rolling restart of Prediction API instances to load the new model. On rollback: reverts the pointer and re-triggers restart.",
        "boundaries": "A CLI tool or simple script — not a long-running service. Invoked manually or by the Shadow Evaluation Service after quality gates pass. The only component authorized to change the active model pointer."
      },
      {
        "name": "Prediction Logger",
        "responsibility": "Asynchronously logs every prediction request (features + predicted value) to the Delivery Data Store for future model evaluation and retraining. Fire-and-forget — never blocks the prediction response.",
        "boundaries": "Embedded as an async side-effect in the Prediction API. Writes to a queue (SQS/Kafka topic) that drains into the Delivery Data Store. Failure here must never impact prediction latency."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Checkout Service (external)",
        "to": "Prediction API",
        "contract": "POST /predict — Request: {weight_kg, distance_km, zone_id, order_time_utc, weather_code, courier_load_count}. Response: {predicted_minutes, confidence_lower, confidence_upper, model_version}. Timeout: 150ms client-side.",
        "coupling_type": "runtime"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction API",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "On startup and on SIGHUP: fetch model artifact for the active version pointer. GET /models/active → {version, artifact_url, feature_schema}.",
        "coupling_type": "deployment-time"
      },
      {
        "from": "Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "POST /models — publishes new model artifact + metadata (metrics on holdout set, feature importance, dataset size/hash). Status set to 'candidate' not 'active'.",
        "coupling_type": "async-batch"
      },
      {
        "from": "Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Delivery Data Store",
        "contract": "SQL/Parquet read of delivery records within the training window. Columns: all input features + actual_delivery_minutes + order_timestamp.",
        "coupling_type": "data"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction Logger",
        "to": "Delivery Data Store",
        "contract": "Async write via message queue. Schema: request features + predicted_minutes + model_version + timestamp. Used to close the feedback loop for retraining.",
        "coupling_type": "async"
      },
      {
        "from": "Shadow Evaluation Service",
        "to": "Prediction API",
        "contract": "Reads prediction log stream. Runs candidate model inference on same inputs. Compares outputs. No direct API calls to Prediction API.",
        "coupling_type": "async"
      },
      {
        "from": "Model Deployment Controller",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "PUT /models/{version}/activate — promotes candidate to active. PUT /models/{version}/rollback — reverts to previous active version.",
        "coupling_type": "operational"
      },
      {
        "from": "Model Deployment Controller",
        "to": "Prediction API",
        "contract": "Sends SIGHUP or triggers rolling restart to reload model. No downtime — instances reload one at a time behind load balancer.",
        "coupling_type": "operational"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "SERVING PATH (hot, <100ms): Checkout Service → Prediction API (in-memory model inference) → response. Side-effect: Prediction Logger async-enqueues request+prediction to message queue → Delivery Data Store. TRAINING PATH (cold, weekly): Delivery Data Store → Training Pipeline (feature engineering → train → evaluate) → Model Registry (candidate). PROMOTION PATH (manual/gated): Shadow Evaluation Service validates candidate on live traffic shadow → Model Deployment Controller promotes in Registry → Prediction API instances reload model. ROLLBACK PATH: Model Deployment Controller reverts active pointer → Prediction API instances reload previous model.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Model Registry (versioned artifact store)",
        "rationale": "Central coordination point between training and serving. Enables rollback by maintaining version history and an active pointer. Decouples training from deployment — training publishes, deployment promotes separately."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Blue-Green Model Deployment",
        "rationale": "New model is validated in shadow mode before promotion. Rollback is a pointer swap, not a redeployment. Minimizes blast radius of bad models."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Embedded inference (model-in-process)",
        "rationale": "Loading the model directly into the Prediction API process (e.g., ONNX Runtime, LightGBM C API) eliminates network hops to a separate model server. Critical for hitting 100ms P99. Avoids the operational complexity of TensorFlow Serving or Triton for a single model."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Async Prediction Logging (fire-and-forget)",
        "rationale": "Logs predictions for retraining feedback loop without adding latency to the serving path. Queue absorbs bursts. Acceptable to lose a small fraction of logs."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Shadow Traffic Evaluation",
        "rationale": "Validates candidate model on real production input distribution before it serves real traffic. Catches data drift and training bugs that offline holdout evaluation misses."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Strangler-friendly API contract",
        "rationale": "Prediction API returns model_version in every response, enabling the checkout service to log and correlate prediction quality. Future path to A/B testing without changing the contract."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Prediction Serving",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["PredictionRequest (value object: immutable feature vector)", "PredictionResponse (value object: predicted minutes + confidence + model version)", "ActiveModel (entity: loaded model artifact + version + feature schema)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Lifecycle",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["ModelVersion (aggregate root: version ID, artifact location, status [candidate|active|retired], metrics, feature schema, created_at)", "PromotionEvent (domain event: version promoted/rolled back, timestamp, actor)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Training",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["TrainingRun (aggregate root: run ID, dataset hash, hyperparameters, holdout metrics, output model version)", "TrainingDataset (value object: time range, record count, feature statistics)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Delivery Data (upstream)",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["DeliveryRecord (entity from logistics platform — we consume, not own)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Delivery Data",
        "downstream": "Training",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Training conforms to the logistics platform's delivery record schema. An ACL layer would be premature for a 4-person team; instead, a thin adapter in the Training Pipeline normalizes column names and types."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Model Lifecycle",
        "downstream": "Prediction Serving",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Model Lifecycle dictates the artifact format and feature schema. Prediction Serving is the customer that consumes model artifacts. The feature schema in the Registry acts as the Published Language."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Training",
        "downstream": "Model Lifecycle",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Training produces candidate models; Model Lifecycle owns the promotion decision and version management."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Prediction Serving",
        "downstream": "Training",
        "relationship": "Prediction logs flow async from Serving to the Delivery Data Store, which Training consumes. No direct coupling — the message queue decouples them."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "In-process model inference instead of dedicated model serving infrastructure (Triton, TF Serving, Seldon)",
      "gains": "Eliminates network hop — saves 5-20ms per call. Drastically simpler operations for a 4-person team. No gRPC serialization overhead. Easier to debug.",
      "sacrifices": "Model format constrained to what the API runtime supports (ONNX, LightGBM, XGBoost native). Cannot serve GPU-accelerated deep learning models without refactoring. Model reload requires process coordination.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Dedicated model serving (Triton/TF Serving) — rejected: adds operational burden and network latency for a single tabular model", "Sidecar model server — rejected: still adds IPC latency and doubles deployment complexity"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Simple S3 + metadata table as Model Registry instead of MLflow/Weights & Biases",
      "gains": "No additional infrastructure to maintain. Full control over promotion logic. 4-person team doesn't need experiment tracking UI for a single model.",
      "sacrifices": "No built-in experiment comparison UI. Manual metric tracking. If team grows or model count increases, will need to migrate.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["MLflow — good but heavy for one model and four engineers", "DVC — good for versioning but weaker on serving integration"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Weekly batch retraining instead of online/incremental learning",
      "gains": "Simpler to validate, debug, and reproduce. Full holdout evaluation possible. Easier rollback semantics. Matches team skill level.",
      "sacrifices": "Model may lag behind sudden distribution shifts (e.g., new zone, weather event). Max staleness is 7 days.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Daily retraining — considered reasonable if data volume supports it, easy to change cadence later", "Online learning — rejected: much harder to validate, debug, and rollback"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Gradient-boosted trees (LightGBM/XGBoost) as the model architecture",
      "gains": "Inference in <5ms for tabular data. Excellent with the feature types described (categorical zones, numerical weight/distance). Interpretable feature importance. Small artifact size (<50MB). No GPU needed.",
      "sacrifices": "Cannot easily incorporate unstructured inputs (e.g., route imagery) in the future. Less capacity for extremely complex nonlinear interactions.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Neural network — rejected: overkill for tabular features, slower inference, harder to interpret, needs GPU for training", "Linear regression — rejected: too simple for feature interactions like zone × time_of_day × weather"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Shadow evaluation window instead of A/B testing for model promotion",
      "gains": "No customers receive predictions from an unvalidated model. Simpler implementation — no traffic splitting infrastructure needed.",
      "sacrifices": "Cannot measure actual impact on customer behavior (e.g., conversion rate). Shadow evaluation uses prediction accuracy as proxy, not business metrics.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["A/B testing with traffic split — deferred: requires more infrastructure, can be added later using the model_version field in responses", "Canary deployment (1% traffic) — good middle ground, recommended as a Phase 2 enhancement"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Model algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "The Prediction API loads any model that conforms to the predict(features) → float interface. Swapping LightGBM for XGBoost, CatBoost, or even an ONNX-exported neural network requires zero API changes. The feature schema in the Registry ensures compatibility."
    },
    {
      "area": "Retraining cadence",
      "evolution_path": "Changing from weekly to daily or triggered-on-drift is a scheduler configuration change. The pipeline itself is idempotent and parameterized by date range."
    },
    {
      "area": "Feature set expansion",
      "evolution_path": "New features (e.g., traffic data, courier rating) are added by: (1) extending the Delivery Data Store ETL, (2) updating the Training Pipeline feature engineering, (3) publishing a new feature schema version in the Registry, (4) updating the Prediction API input contract. The feature schema version in the Registry enforces compatibility."
    },
    {
      "area": "A/B testing and canary",
      "evolution_path": "model_version is already in every response. Adding traffic splitting requires only a thin routing layer in front of Prediction API instances — no model code changes."
    },
    {
      "area": "Multi-model serving",
      "evolution_path": "If the business needs separate models per region or product type, the Registry supports multiple model families. Prediction API routes by a discriminator field. This is a natural extension, not a redesign."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Prediction API latency contract (100ms P99)",
      "reason": "This is a hard constraint from the checkout path. All architectural decisions flow from it — in-process inference, no external feature store lookups, pre-computed features. Relaxing this would unlock simpler but slower designs."
    },
    {
      "area": "Feature schema as contract between Training and Serving",
      "reason": "The feature vector shape and encoding must match exactly between training-time and inference-time. A mismatch silently produces garbage predictions. The schema in the Registry is the enforcement point — this is intentionally rigid."
    },
    {
      "area": "Model artifact format",
      "reason": "Must be loadable in-process by the Prediction API runtime. Constrains model choices to formats like LightGBM native, XGBoost native, or ONNX. Moving to PyTorch/TensorFlow would require rearchitecting the serving layer."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Feature skew between training and serving — features computed differently at training time (batch SQL) vs serving time (real-time API) produce silent prediction degradation",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Extract feature encoding logic into a shared library used by both Training Pipeline and Prediction API. Add a feature distribution monitor that alerts when serving-time feature distributions diverge from training-time distributions. Include feature value histograms in prediction logs."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Model degradation goes undetected between weekly retraining cycles — sudden distribution shift (new zone, extreme weather, courier strike) causes inaccurate predictions for up to 7 days",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Implement a lightweight real-time accuracy monitor: compare predictions against actual delivery times (available ~hours later) and alert when MAE exceeds a threshold. This triggers an emergency retraining run outside the weekly cadence."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Cold start latency — model loading on Prediction API startup takes seconds, causing timeout errors during deployment or scaling events",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Pre-warm instances before adding to load balancer. Cache model artifact locally so startup doesn't depend on S3 availability. Use rolling restarts (never restart all instances simultaneously). Set health check to 'ready' only after model is loaded."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Prediction logging backpressure — if the message queue backs up, it could eventually apply memory pressure on the Prediction API process",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Use a bounded in-process buffer with drop-on-full semantics. Losing some prediction logs is acceptable; impacting checkout latency is not. Monitor queue depth and alert on sustained backlog."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Small team bottleneck — with 2 ML + 2 platform engineers, illness or attrition on either side creates a single point of failure for the serving or training path",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Ensure at least one cross-trained engineer who can operate both paths. Document runbooks for model promotion, rollback, and emergency retraining. Keep the architecture simple enough that any engineer can debug any component."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Stale weather/courier load data at prediction time — if the external data sources for weather or courier load are unavailable, predictions degrade",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Design the model to degrade gracefully with missing features (use default/median imputation for weather and courier load). Monitor feature availability and alert. The model should be trained with synthetic missing-feature scenarios."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Phase 1 (Weeks 1-3): Platform engineers build the Prediction API (Python/FastAPI or Rust for latency, with LightGBM in-process), Model Registry (S3 + Postgres table), and the deployment controller (CLI script). ML engineers build the Training Pipeline (Python, orchestrated by a single Airflow DAG or cron + script) and feature engineering. Phase 2 (Weeks 4-5): Integrate — ML engineers publish a trained model to the Registry, platform engineers deploy it through the Prediction API. Add prediction logging. Phase 3 (Week 6): Shadow evaluation, accuracy monitoring, rollback testing. Run load tests to verify 100ms P99 under expected QPS. Phase 4 (ongoing): Monitor, iterate on features, tune retraining cadence based on observed drift.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "prediction-api/ — FastAPI service: main.py (endpoints), model_loader.py (Registry client + in-memory model), feature_encoder.py (shared encoding logic), prediction_logger.py (async queue writer)",
      "training-pipeline/ — Pipeline code: train.py (orchestrator), feature_engineering.py (imports shared feature_encoder), evaluate.py (holdout + comparison metrics), publish_model.py (Registry client)",
      "shared/feature_schema.py — Canonical feature definition: names, types, encoding rules, version. Used by both prediction-api and training-pipeline to prevent skew.",
      "model-registry/ — Infrastructure: registry_client.py (SDK for interacting with S3 + metadata DB), migrations/ (Postgres schema for model metadata table)",
      "deployment/ — Operational tooling: promote_model.sh (CLI for promotion), rollback_model.sh (CLI for rollback), docker-compose.yml (local dev), terraform/ (infrastructure as code for S3, Postgres, API hosting)",
      "monitoring/ — Alerting configs: accuracy_monitor.py (compares predictions to actuals), feature_drift_monitor.py (distribution checks), dashboards/ (Grafana JSON for model health)"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Shared feature encoding library is the single most important pattern — it prevents training/serving skew. Use the Registry's feature schema version as a compatibility gate: Prediction API refuses to load a model whose feature schema version it doesn't support. Keep the Training Pipeline idempotent: given the same date range and data, it produces the same model. Tag every prediction with model_version for traceability. Use structured logging throughout for debuggability.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT build a feature store — for 6 input features, inline computation in the Prediction API is faster and simpler. A feature store adds latency (network hop) and operational burden that a 4-person team cannot afford.",
      "DO NOT use Python for latency-critical path without benchmarking — if FastAPI + LightGBM doesn't hit 100ms P99, consider Rust with the LightGBM C API or pre-compiled ONNX Runtime. Benchmark early in Week 1.",
      "DO NOT auto-promote models — always require a quality gate (shadow evaluation or manual approval). A bad model in the checkout path directly impacts revenue.",
      "DO NOT store model artifacts in the database — use S3/GCS for artifacts, database for metadata only. Model files can be hundreds of MB.",
      "DO NOT duplicate feature encoding logic — the moment training and serving have separate feature code, skew is inevitable. Shared library or shared config is non-negotiable.",
      "DO NOT skip prediction logging — without it, you cannot evaluate model quality on real traffic or close the retraining feedback loop. This is the most commonly deferred and most painful-to-retrofit component."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 85,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "In-process model inference is the correct serving pattern for 100ms P99 with tabular features",
      "Model Registry with versioning and active pointer enables safe rollback",
      "Gradient-boosted trees are the right model class for this feature set and latency requirement",
      "Shared feature encoding is critical for preventing training/serving skew",
      "This architecture is appropriately scoped for a 4-person team"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Exact technology choice for Prediction API (FastAPI vs Rust) depends on benchmarking — Python may or may not hit 100ms P99 depending on QPS and feature encoding cost",
      "Shadow evaluation window duration (24 hours suggested) needs tuning based on traffic volume and acceptable promotion delay",
      "Whether Airflow is warranted for a single weekly pipeline or a cron job suffices — depends on team's existing infra"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "QPS at checkout is moderate (sub-10K RPS) — extremely high throughput would require horizontal scaling strategy detail",
      "Weather and courier load data are available as pre-computed values at request time (the checkout service provides them), not fetched by the Prediction API from external APIs",
      "The 6 input features are sufficient for V1 — the architecture supports expansion but initial model complexity is low",
      "The team has basic cloud infrastructure (S3, managed Postgres, container hosting) already available",
      "Actual delivery times become available within hours of delivery completion for the feedback loop"
    ]
  }
}

